le to exploitation as well as for survivors striving to leave the sex industry; however, there are also many opportunities to help them. Based on Chrismas’s award-winning research in Manitoba, this book includes gut-wrenching stories from survivors, social workers, police officers, lawmakers, and activists. Representing decades of collective knowledge, Sex Industry Slavery presents first-hand perspectives on the problem as well as proposes practical solutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChild prostitutionzCanada. 0aHuman trafficking victimszCanada. 0aHuman traffickingzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aIndigenous.  aconflict.  aexploitation.  amissing.  amurdered.  apeace.  apolice.  apolicing.  aprostitution.  asex.  asexual.  aslavery.  astory telling.  astrategies.  astudies.  atrafficking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753571140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487535711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487535711.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles